## Review
- Correct: The README already has a strong core idea in multiple places: “Chat should be the control layer — not the destination” (`README.md:16-24`), “Chat in → workspace out” (`README.md:31-33`), and “agents open UI, not just text” (`README.md:64-71`). Those all point toward the same product truth: the value is not chat itself, but turning agent actions into inspectable workspace state.
- Blocker: The page currently presents multiple top-level angles instead of one crisp one. The opening hero says “Bring your agent skills and get a fully agent-centered app” and “agent-centered app” (`README.md:5-7`), then the body pivots to “chat as control layer” (`README.md:16-24`), then to “framework for building agent-native software” (`README.md:61-62`), then to “production-grade agent, workspace, and app-shell packages” (`README.md:12`). These are adjacent ideas, but not the same promise, so the message feels broadened instead of sharpened.
- Note: Audience is mixed too early. The hero and “A different belief” speak to product builders and framing (`README.md:5-33`), while the very next sections shift into package inventory and repo composition (`README.md:39-91`). This makes the page read partly like a product homepage, partly like a monorepo maintainer README, and partly like package docs. The result is diluted positioning.
- Note: Several ideas repeat with slightly different wording rather than compounding the argument. Repeats include: “chat is the control layer” (`README.md:20`, `README.md:35`), “workspace is where work appears” (`README.md:35`, `README.md:48-56`), “agent opens UI / renders outputs” (`README.md:26-29`, `README.md:68`, `README.md:84`), and “composable stack of core + agent + workspace” (`README.md:39-47`, `README.md:73-91`). This repetition takes up prime top-of-page space without increasing precision.
- Note: Some framing is vague or padded. Examples: “real product surface” (`README.md:7`) is broad and non-specific; “The goal is software whose interface can adapt to the work” (`README.md:29`) is evocative but abstract; “Composable deployment model” (`README.md:94-99`) sounds infrastructure-heavy without clarifying user value. These phrases could be tightened around one concrete outcome.
- Note: The “What you can build” section broadens the scope too much (`README.md:37-42`). “browser-based coding agents” aligns strongly, but “internal tools with agent-driven workflows,” “copilots inside custom workspaces,” and “apps whose interface adapts to the task” move from specific to generic. That weakens the sharper, more ownable angle.
- Note: The package naming and product naming create mild conceptual drift. The repo title is “Boring UI” (`README.md:3`), but the quickstart emphasizes a CLI (`README.md:111-123`), while the core description emphasizes app shell/auth/database (`README.md:145-156`). Without a single framing sentence tying these together, readers may not know whether Boring UI is primarily a coding-agent product, a framework, or a monorepo of primitives.
- Note: The current top section likely over-explains architecture before earning it. “Packages at a glance,” “Design principles,” “How the stack is composed,” and “Package composition” all appear before quickstart (`README.md:39-91`). For a README, that is a lot of internal taxonomy before the reader gets a simple answer to “what is this and why would I use it?”
- Note: The strongest differentiator appears to be: agents do work by creating and controlling visible workspace artifacts, not by stopping at chat. That should probably become the singular angle, with package and architecture sections recast as proof, not co-equal messaging themes.

